## Violation Patterns

### 1. Sensitive Data in Console Logs

```typescript
// ❌ VIOLATION: Sensitive data logged
console.log('User data:', { ssn: '123-45-6789', dob: '1990-01-01' });
console.log('Processing record:', record);  // Full object
console.error('Failed to save', entity);

// ✅ COMPLIANT: Reference IDs only
console.log('Processing record', { id: 123 });
console.error('Failed to save', { id: 123, error: error.message });
```

### 2. Sensitive Data in Error Responses

```typescript
// ❌ VIOLATION: Data returned to client
catch (error) {
  res.status(500).json({ 
    error: error.message,
    data: entity  // Includes sensitive fields
  });
}

// ✅ COMPLIANT: Generic error, log details server-side
catch (error) {
  logger.error('Save failed', { entityId, error: error.message });
  res.status(500).json({ 
    error: 'Failed to save record',
    message: 'Please try again or contact support.'
  });
}
```

### 3. Sensitive Data in API Responses

```typescript
// ❌ VIOLATION: Returning raw database row
return res.json({ data: entity });

// ✅ COMPLIANT: Explicit field selection (allowlist)
return res.json({
  data: {
    id: entity.id,
    name: entity.display_name,
    status: entity.status
    // Exclude: SSN, DOB, address, phone, etc.
  }
});
```

### 4. Sensitive Data in Frontend State

```typescript
// ❌ VIOLATION: Storing full entity in state
this.store.dispatch(loadEntity({ entity: fullEntity }));

// ✅ COMPLIANT: Store only necessary non-sensitive fields
this.store.dispatch(loadEntity({ 
  entity: {
    id: fullEntity.id,
    name: fullEntity.displayName,
    status: fullEntity.status
  }
}));
```

### 5. Sensitive Data in URLs/Query Parameters

```typescript
// ❌ VIOLATION: Sensitive data in URL
router.get('/api/users/ssn/:ssn', ...);
this.http.get(`/api/search?email=${email}`);

// ✅ COMPLIANT: Use IDs only
router.get('/api/users/:userId', ...);
this.http.post('/api/search', { userId });
```

